<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-261-425  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 261 425.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  Jan 1989 v12 n1 p34(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A new dimension in medical research: modeling in 3D givesresearchers new clues for solving the mysteries of human disease.andO;(three-dimensional image processing in medical research)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kiely, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The pace of 3D image processing in medical research isaccelerating due largely to the emergence of hardware and softwaretools that can capture real data and render it on fast andpowerful machines.andP;  Data can be captured using such techniques asmagnetic resonance imaging or X-ray crystallography.andP;  Data arethen modeled using interactive graphics software.andP;  Images can berotated in real time and can be viewed in any plane using powerfulcomputers, thereby giving medical researchers new insights aboutbiological processes.andP;  Research projects utilizing 3D imaging atseveral US medical centers are described.andP;  Little researchinformation is shared, however, due largely to proprietary issuesthat foster secrecy and academic competition, and there isconsiderable expensive, duplicated effort.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer GraphicsApplicationsMedical ResearchTechnologyTrendsThree-Dimensional GraphicsImage Processing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>